The Ministry of Health on Saturday recorded
four COVID-19 cases from 2,121 samples tested in the last 24 hours, marking a
positivity rate of 0.2 per cent. Of the cases, three are foreigners while one is
a Kenyan and all the four are males. The youngest is a 29-year-old while the
oldest is 63 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now
323,609 and cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,565,081. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi
recorded 3 cases and Kwale had one case. In the vaccination campaign, a total of
17,810,207 vaccines had been administered across the country as of March 15,
2022. "Of these, 16,289,410 are doses
administered to the adult population (18 years and above),” Health Cabinet
Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement to newsrooms. “Another 1,229,600 are doses administered to
those between 15 to 17 years, while 291,197 are booster doses.” The CS added that the total number of
vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 1,231 while the total number of
people fully vaccinated is 1,061. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated is 30.3
per cent, he said, adding that the government is working towards vaccinating a
targeted population of 2,246,033. Kagwe noted that five patients recovered from
the disease, all of them from the Home Based and Isolation Care program. The
total recoveries are now at 317,811. Meanwhile, no death was recorded, thus the
cumulative fatalities stand at 5,649. A total of 11 patients are currently admitted
to various health facilities countrywide, while 122 are under the Home-Based
Isolation and Care program.  “No patient is in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU) or on supplemental oxygen or in the general wards. No patient is in the
High Dependency Unit (HDU),” Kagwe said.